        "timestamp": "2019-04-11 06:15:43.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 9:\n\n> Josh - not sure how you or I got the guard working in the first\n > place. The storing of xacml.properties was not working properly.\n > Please take a close look at those changes.\n\nI've done a quick look over the changes and nothing pops out at me as being off. I'll try to dig in further, though I may not have anything useful to say until tomorrow as I'm running out of energy for the night.",
        "patchset_number": 9
      },
      {
        "id": "2f5b0d90deabf8d8fef59066746aff8d0833f58d",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 423,
          "name": "Joshua Reich",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jreich@research.att.com",
          "username": "josh.reich"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-04-11 06:39:01.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 9:\n\n> It looks like frequency limiter is failing - but the operations\n > history PIP doesn't get called. Possibly because the check for the\n > current time is failing. Perhaps there is a bug converting UTC\n > time.\n\nI'm unable to replicate the failure locally at the moment. Looking at the Jenkins output, it seems to be the same issue I was having a day or two ago on change 84549. I'm increasingly inclined to believe it's some sort of heisenbug, most likely in either this code or the att xacml implementation. The key symptom is that sometime the PIP runs fine and other times simply fails to run at all. Unfortunately, at the moment, I don't have a working hypothesis for what might be causing it. @Pam, can you tell me how you detected that xacml.properties wasn't being stored properly?",
        "patchset_number": 9
      },
      {
        "id": "20b887a07189ae4ce1e96e7be5605e987650c45e",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 57,
